ingredients.Name: medium gold potatoes, peeled and cubed

directions.Direction: Place a large pot of water on the stove on high heat. Add half of the potatoes and bring to a boil. Cover and cook until fork tender (approximately 10-15 minutes). Add to a blender with 1 c of broth and blend until smooth. Set aside.

Add olive oil to a sauce pot on medium heat. Once hot, add in onion, celery, and carrots. Saut√© for 5-8 minutes and veggies are softened. Add in garlic and spices. Cook for 30 seconds or until fragrant. Add in the rest of the potatoes and broth and cover. Bring to a simmer, stirring occasionally. Cook until potatoes are fork tender.

While the soup is cooking, preheat oven to the broil setting. Add bread to a sheet pan and drizzle with olive oil. Mix with hands until most pieces are coated. Broil for 3-6 minutes or until bread is nice and toasted, being sure to mix halfway through. Remove from oven and sprinkle lightly with salt. Set aside.
Next, add pancetta to a pan over medium-high heat and cook until crispy. Set aside.
Add in corn, blended potatoes, and heavy cream to the soup pot. Cook for an additional 3-5 minutes, the soup should thicken slightly.
Tip: if the soup does not reach your desired consistency, mix 1 tsp of cornstarch and 1 tsp water in a bowl and mix that in.
Serve and garnish with croutons, pancetta, and chives.
Preheat oven to 200 degrees.
Cut bread into small cubes.
Add 3 c of cubed bread to a baking sheet and spread around evenly.
Bake for 30-45 minutes or until bread has dried out (be sure to mix every so often).
Remove from oven and let cool.
While the bread cubes are baking, add butter to a pan over medium heat.
Once melted, add in onion, celery, and dry spices. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Saute until onion is translucent (approximately 5-10 minutes).
Remove from pan and let cool.
Add bread cubes, sauted veggies, and parsley to a large bowl.
Mix in chicken broth 1/4 c at a time. The bread should be moist but soaked (you may not use all of the broth).
Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.
Strain canned clams but save the clam juice (you'll need that later).
Drizzle oil in a large sauce pan over medium heat.
Once hot, add in garlic and anchovies. Cook for 3 minutes, stirring often.
Add in the red pepper flakes.
Add pasta to water and cook 2 minutes less than al dente (don't forget to reserve water).
Pour wine into the sauce pan and reduces slightly. This takes a few minutes.
Add in the lemon juice and clam juice. Bring to a simmer.
Add in the clams and simmer on low for a 1-2 minutes.
Add in the linguini, stirring constantly (this will help emulsify the sauce). Cook until al dente. Add in extra pasta water if needed.
Turn heat off and mix in the butter and parsley. Season with salt and pepper, to taste.
Garnish with lemon zest and parsley.
Add oil to a large pan or wok over medium-high heat.
Once hot, add in onion and season with salt and white pepper. Saute for a few minutes.
Push onions to the side of the pan and crack eggs in. Scramble the eggs.
Add in the rice and mix.
Create a hole in the middle of the rice and add the butter. Melt and mix everything together.
Add in soy sauce and mix. Continue saut√©ing the rice for an addiontional 3 minutes, stirring occationally.
Taste and add extra soy sauce if needed. Set aside and keep warm.
